```ts
function findDuplicates(arr: number[]): number[] {
  const result: number[] = [];
  for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
    for (let j = i + 1; j < arr.length; j++) {
      if (arr[i] === arr[j] && !result.includes(arr[i])) {
        result.push(arr[i]);
      }
    }
  }
  return result;
}
```

📋 SUMMARY: Reviewing slow `findDuplicates` function — O(n³) complexity due to nested loops plus `includes` check.

🔍 ANALYSIS:
- Outer + inner loop = O(n²)
- `result.includes()` inside that = another O(n) scan, making it O(n³) worst case
- For large arrays, this compounds quickly

⚡ ACTIONS: Here's an O(n) replacement using a `Set`:

```ts
function findDuplicates(arr: number[]): number[] {
  const seen = new Set<number>();
  const duplicates = new Set<number>();
  for (const num of arr) {
    if (seen.has(num)) {
      duplicates.add(num);
    } else {
      seen.add(num);
    }
  }
  return [...duplicates];
}
```

📖 STORY EXPLANATION:
1. Original has three nested O(n) operations — two `for` loops plus `includes` — giving O(n³)
2. `Set.has()` and `Set.add()` are both O(1) average, replacing all three expensive operations
3. `seen` tracks every number encountered; `duplicates` collects only repeats
4. Single pass through the array — O(n) time, O(n) space
5. On a 10,000-element array: ~1 trillion ops → ~10,000 ops

